@@ -1965,6 +1965,16 @@ public:
                 res = make(commute,pf,comm_equiv);
                 break;
             }
+            case PR_AND_ELIM: {
+                std::vector<ast> rule_ax, res_conc;
+                ast piv = conc(prem(proof,0));
+                rule_ax.push_back(make(Not,piv));
+                rule_ax.push_back(con);
+                ast pf = iproof->make_axiom(rule_ax);
+                res_conc.push_back(con);
+                res = iproof->make_resolution(piv,res_conc,pf,args[0]);
+                break;
+            }
             default:
                 pfgoto(proof);
                 assert(0 && "translate_main: unsupported proof rule");

```

> The project seems to be dead, anyway. This discussion is pointless without a maintainer chiming in.

@drdaeman Chiming in! BTW, the project is not dead anymore.


I believe that the current `(Latitude, Longitude)` order was influenced by the one of the `Point` class (for consistency), which order, in turn, was influenced by the order of coordinates in DMS representation for display (which is usually [`lat, long, alt`](https://gis.stackexchange.com/a/6048)).

The latlon vs lonlat order is a common source of confusion, and changing default order won't help at all.

I can understand both: latlon order is more convenient for display and lonlat order clearly maps on the X-Y order of cartesian coordinates (assuming that y>0 is North and x>0 is East with the center at `0N 0E`).


I also can understand why the default latlon order (`y, x`) of `distance` (rather than `Point`) might be confusing: the majority (IMO) of software uses lonlat order. I faced the same difficulty when I was working with Django Point (which also uses x/y for lon/lat respectively). Here I support @drdaeman's idea of being explicit in this regard. But I don't think that it's worth deprecating accepting the tuple in latlon order, because it might work for some people just fine. But for the rest of us, converting from lonlat to latlon (actually, a `Point` instance) explicitly should be the way to go.


> I don't see how the change I am proposing will break existing code @drdaeman, @adah1972. I am saying that you keep the input as [(lat, lon}] to maintain compatibility. But add a Boolean switch to accept the arguments as [(lon, lat)] as well. That will be more succinct than either using Point instances, or creating another API. The rest of the code will remain the same.

@dragonator4 I'm strongly against this. First of all, what should the behavior be for `distance(Point(...), Point(...), xy=True)`? How to deal with altitude? Not to mention that it'd significantly complicate changing the signature in future (i.e. changing the default order or deprecating tuples instead of `Point`s at all). It's not about the amount of the code to be changed, it's about ease of maintenance. I personally see a better solution to this problem (see below).

> It would be good to introduce a pair of shortcut helper functions, latlon(y, x) and lonlat(x, y). I believe they would be especially useful when some foreign API gives one a tuple: lonlat(*coords) looks explicit (almost to the extent of being self-explanatory) yet concise.

@drdaeman I completely agree on this one. I guess that `distance(lonlat(x, y), lonlat(x, y))` is the way to go in this situation.

`latlon` function might seem redundant for now, however I'd still introduce it as well, to be able to change the default order in future (though today me is strongly against it, but depriving the future us of that ability would be obnoxious).

> Point should accept abbreviated lat and lon kwargs. Possibly, allow lng spelling as well. Full words are nice but cumbersome, and I doubt anyone would be confused by abbreviations.

@drdaeman Great idea! I'd gladly accept a PR for that.

> Say, a new geopy.distance_xy that provides vincenty and great_circle.

@adah1972 I don't think that polluting the interface this way is a good idea. This increases cohesion between distance calculation and coordinates representation greatly, which complicates maintenance.

To sum up, my suggestions are:
- `lonlat(x, y, z=0)` and `latlon(y, x, z=0)` functions returning a `Point` should be added
- docs should be updated to explain the lonlat vs latlon problem and provide examples with `distance(lonlat(x, y), lonlat(x, y))`

@dragonator4 @adah1972 does this solution seem reasonable to you?

If anyone is willing to open a PR for this – please do!

@wjakob - I think the fix is just a matter of changing pybind11.h line 263 from:

```C++
                if (chain->class_ != rec->class_)
```
to
```C++
                if (chain->class_ != rec->class_ || chain->scope != rec->scope)
```

(without this, the same chain is shared for static method for both the parent and derived classes, since both have `class_` set to null).

