However, the test_webcam in test_ffmpeg.py needs to be updated to something like below. You currently check <video2> but on OS X the first camera is at <video0> so unless the person has 3 cameras this test will fail. Using the below code the test passes on my system.

```python
def test_webcam():
    need_internet()

    def check_cam(index):
        try:
            imageio.read('<video{0}>'.format(index))
        except Exception:
            return False
        return True

    # See if there is a camera on the first 3 indexes
    for i in range(3):
        if check_cam(i):
            # Found a camera, it worked.
            return

    # Didn't find a camera
    skip('no web cam')
```

@certik, the skip can be conditional: in this case some tests will be skipped if NumPy is not available (since they rely on it).

The xfail is maybe not quite as useful, I see it as a way of documenting a desired behaviour which one maybe have not had time to implement yet (or if it fails due to a bug in an upstream package which might not be fixed any time soon). It is often at a late stage you realize that you will not be able to make a test pass, so you're faced with a few options: comment it out, throw it away or mark it as xfail.

Anyways, I don't want to be religous about these things and I'll happily comment things out if that is preferred to xfailing. And giving it some thought, the conditional skip may be implemented like this:

```
def test_ravel():
    if HAVE_NUMPY:
        assert np.ravel(some_array) == [1, 2, 3]
    else:
        assert True
```

It would still work with the minor drawback that quite a few tests reported as "Passing" would in reality not have been really run.

So I could comment out xfail tests and refactor skipped ones accordingly if you'd like.

@ezyang the nature of the discussion I posted was about naturalness. On one hand, your example is still overloading by inputs (albeit they are pointers to the outputs) in its simplest level of abstraction (i.e., a parser's prospective, thus the most conducive to interpretation); on the other, I was unable to see how your example workaround to achieve "overloading by return types" address my concern.. That is to say, possibility != naturalness. 

> Now, the internal representation doesn't necessarily correspond one-to-one with how you should implement a DSL for defining ONNX nodes. 

This is exactly my question. Why bother having different representations? I can only see that your point about PyTorch adds to the up side of having a unified way of defining ONNX nodes and generating ONNX nodes in the exporter/importer. What if the user wants to edit the graph exported from PyTorch and could not find the equivalent of `outputs` parameter in the ONNX graph proto?

